"><strong>here</strong></a>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','We have a new artist','See the incredible work of Chelsea Gibson','publish','closed','closed','','new-artist-join-the-road-gallery','','','2014-03-14 23:33:06','2014-03-14 23:33:06','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=1001',50,'news','',0),(1002,2,'2014-03-14 23:29:07','2014-03-14 23:29:07','','Mark Reading','','inherit','open','open','','mark-reading-2','','','2014-03-14 23:29:07','2014-03-14 23:29:07','',1001,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Mark-Reading1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1006,2,'2014-03-16 12:03:32','2014-03-16 12:03:32','<strong>Silt in a Pond by Susan Klein</strong>\r\n\r\nAlthough my work is abstract, the motives behind them are often narrative and literary.  What I\'m reading, where I live, where I travel - these are absolutely influential.  I was reading Margaret Atwood\'s \"The Blind Assasin\" a few months ago while working on this painting.  There is a particular passage in it  \"Time: old cold time, old sorrow, settling down in layers like silt in a pond\".  I love everything about this sentence and it helped steer the direction of this painting.  <em>Silt in a Pond</em> began from a snapshot I took on the street in Montreal of a pile of wood and construction leftovers leaning against a brick building.  On the left hand edge and very bottom of the painting, the surface is sanded, and you can see the remains of the original image.  As the painting developed, I wanted it to be weighted on the bottom, pushed down by an airy, clean, luminescent color.  To me, this painting feels simultaneously dense, heavy and claustrophobic yet light, spatial and open.  It is stratified, both top to bottom and front to back.  I owe a few titles of paintings and narrative ideas about time to Atwood.  Maybe it is fitting that this is a Canadian-sourced painting (but that is coincidental).  It is the rare writer who can do what she does with language.','Featured Work: Silt in a Pond','Discover the story behind Susan Klein\'s Silt in a Pond in the artist\'s own words','publish','closed','closed','','featured-work-silt-in-a-pond','','','2014-03-16 12:03:32','2014-03-16 12:03:32','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=1006',51,'news','',0),(1007,2,'2014-03-16 11:59:04','2014-03-16 11:59:04','','W05KwKnu0Fx3Q36V','','inherit','open','open','','w05kwknu0fx3q36v-2','','','2014-03-16 11:59:04','2014-03-16 11:59:04','',1006,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/W05KwKnu0Fx3Q36V.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1008,2,'2014-03-19 23:32:40','2014-03-19 23:32:40','Exciting news! The Road Gallery has been selected to partner with Grand Cercle des Vins de Bordeaux to showcase the work of three of our artists at an exclusive wine tasting event in NYC. For 50% off tickets use the coupon code roadgallery. To purchase tickets using the coupon code, click <a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/e/grand-cercle-des-vins-de-bordeaux-wine-tasting-tickets-10695337041\"><strong>here</strong></a>\r\n\r\n<strong>Details of the event</strong>\r\n\r\nOn Wednesday April 9th, for one day only, 38 winemakers from the Right Bank and the Left Bank of Bordeaux will treat New Yorkers to an exclusive unveiling of their most prized possessions-- the most widely celebrated 2011 and 2010 vintages. The event, held at Manhattan Penthouse, will begin at 6:30pm and run until 8:30pm. Guests are invited to take in panoramic views of the New York City skyline from the top floor of a historic Fifth Avenue building, and each ticket holder will also be treated to both a cheese tasting and sweet and savory offerings from Canele by Celine. An art exhibition, featuring Gabriela Brave Clavello and three distinguished artists from The Road Gallery, will also be on display. This is your chance to rub elbows with some of the industry’s most respected winemakers and explore some of the finest wines that France has to offer. The tasting includes a generous Silent Auction, featuring rare to find Magnums of prestigious Bordeaux wines, and benefits ACE, The Association of Community Employment Programs for the Homeless.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Calling all wine lovers','The Road Gallery is partnering with Grand Cercle des Vins de Bordeaux','publish','closed','closed','','do-you-love-wine','','','2014-03-19 23:36:45','2014-03-19 23:36:45','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=1008',46,'news','',0),(1009,2,'2014-03-19 23:32:32','2014-03-19 23:32:32','','winegrandcercle','','inherit','open','open','','winegrandcercle','','','2014-03-19 23:32:32','2014-03-19 23:32:32','',1008,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/winegrandcercle.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1011,2,'2014-03-22 13:55:07','2014-03-22 13:55:07','Here is the first look at the newest artwork by Road Gallery favorite Kyle Utter - Portiere.  Check back soon for more information about the piece.','Sneak peek','Be the first to see the newest work by Kyle Utter','publish','closed','closed','','sneak-peek','','','2014-03-22 14:14:48','2014-03-22 14:14:48','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=1011',48,'news','',0),(1012,2,'2014-03-21 21:51:59','2014-03-21 21:51:59','','Portiere','','inherit','open','open','','portiere','','','2014-03-21 21:51:59','2014-03-21 21:51:59','',1011,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Portiere.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1013,2,'2014-03-21 21:56:41','2014-03-21 21:56:41','','Portiere','','inherit','open','open','','portiere-2','','','2014-03-21 21:56:41','2014-03-21 21:56:41','',1011,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Portiere1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1014,2,'2014-03-22 15:34:25','2014-03-22 15:34:25','<strong>Year:</strong> 2013\r\n\r\n<strong>Height:</strong> 40\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Width:</strong> 32\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Medium:</strong> Oil on panel','Summer Grid','','publish','open','open','','summer-grid','','','2014-03-22 15:34:25','2014-03-22 15:34:25','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?p=1014',261,'post','',0),(1015,2,'2014-03-22 15:34:07','2014-03-22 15:34:07','','lZ8aYq3mEcrYH3Mp','','inherit','open','open','','lz8ayq3mecryh3mp','','','2014-03-22 15:34:07','2014-03-22 15:34:07','',1014,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/lZ8aYq3mEcrYH3Mp.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1018,2,'2014-03-23 13:12:05','2014-03-23 13:12:05','<strong>Almost Touching by Susan Klein</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Almost Touching </em>began as a painting of  a construction site.  The warm autumn light fell upon crossbeams and concrete blocks, steel rods, and other building detritus.  After this initial image was laid down, I moved slowly on this painting, making a decision, letting it sit, coming back to it later.   To my mind, a work is resolved when I know what the main action is, when some sort of verb asserts itself.  I almost painted completely over the original image, sanded it all down, responded to the forms, sanded again, and so on.  Eventually this idea emerged of these two forms coming so close to each other, but not making contact.  I liked this charged tension between the two shapes that hover over this semi-landscape.  The erotic potential of forms!','Featured Work: Almost Touching','Read the story behind Susan Klein\'s Almost Touching in her own words','publish','closed','closed','','featured-work-almost-touching','','','2014-03-23 13:13:22','2014-03-23 13:13:22','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=1018',49,'news','',0),(1019,2,'2014-03-23 13:11:47','2014-03-23 13:11:47','','hx18VPv5Z8g5opZY','','inherit','open','open','','hx18vpv5z8g5opzy-2','','','2014-03-23 13:11:47','2014-03-23 13:11:47','',1018,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/hx18VPv5Z8g5opZY.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1023,2,'2014-03-30 12:44:51','2014-03-30 12:44:51','Road Gallery artist Haylee Anne was recently interviewed by Managing Editor Amanda Silberling for the electric and edgy literary  journal Winter Tangerine Review.   Read the complete interview <strong><a href=\"http://wintertangerine.com/haylee-anne-interview\">here</a>.  </strong>Congratulations Haylee Anne on this interview and your incredible work. We\'re so proud of you.','Haylee Anne Interview','Winter Tangerine Review explores her work and influences','publish','closed','closed','','haylee-anne-interview','','','2014-03-30 12:51:23','2014-03-30 12:51:23','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=news&#038;p=1023',47,'news','',0),(1024,2,'2014-03-30 12:42:49','2014-03-30 12:42:49','','Mademoiselle Un_HA_7.16.13','','inherit','open','open','','mademoiselle-un_ha_7-16-13','','','2014-03-30 12:42:49','2014-03-30 12:42:49','',1023,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Mademoiselle-Un_HA_7.16.13.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1025,2,'2014-03-30 12:44:19','2014-03-30 12:44:19','','Mad Un','','inherit','open','open','','mad-un-3','','','2014-03-30 12:44:19','2014-03-30 12:44:19','',1023,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Mad-Un.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1027,2,'2014-03-30 23:36:24','2014-03-30 23:36:24','<div dir=\"ltr\">\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nArtist Kara Smith lives and works in Brooklyn, New York.  She is currently enrolled in the Masters of Art Education Program at Brooklyn College having received her BFA from the Art Institute in Boston. She teaches art classes at the Fort Greene Co-op School, as well as private classes.  Before pursing arts education, she worked as a dresser at the Metropolitan Opera, was a freelance art director and prop stylist, and an arts administrator at galleries in Boston, Los Angeles and New York.  Her work has been exhibited throughout New York.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nHer recent paintings capture the significance of moments ordinarily overlooked.  Drawing from dreams, memories, personal anecdotes, archetypal symbols and myths, she composes worlds, whether real or imagined, that evoke a faint sense of familiarity.  This feeling of ghostly memory fascinates Smith and highlights the influential nature of social memory and how it affects the way our cultures perceives its history. Her process is greatly affected by its content, and seems to take on an almost ritualistic role.  She layers applications of acrylic, charcoal, chalk and graphite to evoke, both literally and physically, the passage of time.  Her 2012 series of large scale paintings focus on the survival of singular structures left behind.  These landscape portraits spotlight buildings, which through their uniqueness, express the isolation of their current surroundings.  The dynamic of their antiquated existence in present locales is a reminder of a bygone era.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</div>','Kara Smith','','publish','closed','closed','','kara-smith','','','2014-10-29 14:26:06','2014-10-29 14:26:06','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=artists&#038;p=1027',15,'artists','',0),(1028,2,'2014-03-30 23:36:09','2014-03-30 23:36:09','','Without Memory hi res','','inherit','open','open','','without-memory-hi-res','','','2014-03-30 23:36:09','2014-03-30 23:36:09','',1027,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Without-Memory-hi-res.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1029,2,'2014-03-30 23:41:32','2014-03-30 23:41:32','<strong>Year: </strong>2014\r\n\r\n<strong>Height: </strong>9.75\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Width: </strong>9.75\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Medium: </strong>Acrylic and graphite on canvas','Without Memory','','publish','open','open','','without-memory','','','2014-11-18 14:15:10','2014-11-18 14:15:10','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?p=1029',260,'post','',0),(1030,2,'2014-03-30 23:41:14','2014-03-30 23:41:14','','Without Memory hi res','','inherit','open','open','','without-memory-hi-res-2','','','2014-03-30 23:41:14','2014-03-30 23:41:14','',1029,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/Without-Memory-hi-res1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(1032,2,'2014-03-30 23:43:46','2014-03-30 23:43:46','<st