'2015-02-06 21:23:28','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?p=2370',165,'post','',0),(2371,2,'2015-02-06 16:23:06','2015-02-06 21:23:06','','recovery_drawing_saint_joan_8_web','','inherit','open','open','','recovery_drawing_saint_joan_8_web','','','2015-02-06 16:23:06','2015-02-06 21:23:06','',2370,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/recovery_drawing_saint_joan_8_web.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2374,2,'2015-02-06 17:07:08','2015-02-06 22:07:08','For many years, drawing was part of my daily practice until it drifted off in favor of jumping directly into painting and sculpting. Even when I did draw, transcribing sketches into paintings was never part of my process. I view both mediums as singular and separate pursuits. I had almost abandoned drawing completely until it unexpectedly re-entered my life last summer. In July 2014, I underwent surgery on the lumbar portion of my spine. A double laminectomy and double microdiscectomy were performed on the L-4, L-5, and S-1. After this delightful surgery, I spent innumerable hours lying in bed and on the couch. It was during this time, and with the foresight and encouragement of my girlfriend, that I began to draw again.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_2347\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"428\"]<img class=\"wp-image-2347 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/recovery_drawing_onassis_10_web-e1423255634742.jpg\" alt=\"recovery_drawing_onassis_10_web\" width=\"428\" height=\"600\" /> Recovery Drawing Onassis 10[/caption]\r\n\r\nDrawing and obsessive viewing of soccer matches dominated the waking part of my days, and much of the first few months of my recovery. Initially, I only scribed <a title=\"Joseph O’Neal\" href=\"http://localhost/artists/joseph-oneal/\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\">Onassis drawings</span></strong></a>. Over and over, these drawings poured out by the hundreds. I was in to the fourth and fifth weeks of recovery before I began to embrace the non-objective side of my process that has dominated my oeuvre. I was unconscious of this until many months later when, with the help of my girlfriend, I began to analyze this happening.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_2332\" align=\"alignnone\" width=\"419\"]<img class=\"wp-image-2332 size-full\" src=\"http://localhost/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/recovery_drawing_onassis_5-e1423253676299.jpg\" alt=\"recovery_drawing_onassis_5\" width=\"419\" height=\"600\" /> Recovery Drawing Onassis 5[/caption]\r\n\r\nI discovered that the repetition, rules and structure of the Onassis drawings provided me with comfort in the wake of the vulnerability of my situation. It was during this down time that I began to understand the role that the Onassis pieces play in my work as a whole. Just as Jacqueline Onassis is a contradiction in her own right; i.e. fortunate and tragic, the Onassis pieces are a contradiction to the rest of my oeuvre. For something to exist it has to have a contradiction; the color black is the contradiction to the color white, the sky is the contradiction to the ground. Through this discovery I have come to the conclusion that for my work to exist I must make these Onassis pieces, I must have the contradiction. The Onassis works contain structure and rules whereas my other work is lawless. They rely on each other in order to be effective.\r\n\r\nDiscover more artwork by <a title=\"Joseph O’Neal\" href=\"http://localhost/artists/joseph-oneal/\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\">Joseph O\'Neal</span></strong></a>. They will also be featured in our <a href=\"http://localhost/news/home-tour-art-sale/\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\">Art Sale</span></strong></a> on Sunday February 22nd, 2015 in Hell\'s Kitchen, NYC.','Onassis To The Rescue','Artist Joseph O\'Neal shares his journey of recovery','publish','open','open','','onassis-to-the-rescue','','','2015-02-16 14:56:28','2015-02-16 19:56:28','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=blog&#038;p=2374',14,'blog','',0),(2380,2,'2015-02-10 10:03:11','2015-02-10 15:03:11','','HealthRight Form','','publish','closed','closed','','acf_healthright-form','','','2015-02-10 10:03:11','2015-02-10 15:03:11','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=acf&#038;p=2380',0,'acf','',0),(2381,2,'2015-02-10 10:05:12','2015-02-10 15:05:12','[gravityform id=\"2\" name=\"HealthRight Image Order\" title=\"false\" description=\"false\" ajax=\"true\"]','Order Prints','','publish','open','open','','order-prints','','','2015-02-10 10:05:12','2015-02-10 15:05:12','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?page_id=2381',7,'page','',0),(2383,2,'2015-02-10 10:23:50','2015-02-10 15:23:50','HealthRight International builds lasting access to health for excluded communities, employing a human rights-based approach and working closely with community partners to improve local capacity and advance the inclusivity of health systems. In 2014, HealthRight partnered with photographer Daniel Jack Lyons on a series of images called Portraits of Resilience. The series celebrates the triumph of excluded communities around the world over disease and discrimination.\r\n\r\nExcluded populations – including orphans, street youth, minorities of all types, drug users, survivors of torture, sex workers, and more – bear a disproportionately large burden of ill health and human rights violations in virtually every society around the world. Stigma, misguided laws, and myopic institutions perpetuate a vicious cycle of disease, discrimination and violence that ensnares these communities. These photographs feature individuals who have benefitted from HealthRight’s work in Kenya, Nepal, Ukraine and the USA.\r\n\r\nThe photographs will be sold and auctioned at two benefit events, one in LA and one in NYC, with all proceeds going to support HealthRight\'s work with excluded populations.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff6600;\"><strong><a href=\"https://healthright.org/events/portraits-resilience/\"><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\">Sonce Alexander Gallery, 2634 South La Cienega Boulevard, Los Angeles, CA 90034</span>\r\n</a></strong><span style=\"color: #000000;\"><a style=\"color: #000000;\" href=\"https://healthright.org/events/portraits-resilience/\">February 28, 2015, 6:00pm - 8:00pm</a></span></span>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"https://healthright.org/events/portraits-resilience-nyc/\"><strong><span style=\"color: #ff6600;\">Rogue Space Chelsea, 508 West 26th Street, New York, NY 10001\r\n</span></strong><span style=\"color: #000000;\">March 12, 2015, 6:00pm - 8:00pm<strong>\r\n</strong></span></a>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"color: #ff6600;\"><strong>The photographs are also available for purchase here</strong></span>. To place your order, click on the image you want to buy and then click <em>Order Prints. </em>You will be able to select the size and quantity. After completing the form, press <em>Submit</em>.  Once your order has been received by HealthRight, a representative will contact you to take payment details.','Portraits of Resilience','','publish','closed','closed','','portraits-of-resilience','','','2015-05-28 10:04:17','2015-05-28 14:04:17','',0,'http://theroadgallery.com/?post_type=artists&#038;p=2383',25,'artists','',0),(2384,2,'2015-02-10 10:23:35','2015-02-10 15:23:35','','Portraits of Resilience','','inherit','open','open','','healthright_gallery_coverimage_72','','','2015-02-10 10:23:47','2015-02-10 15:23:47','',2383,'http://theroadgallery.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Healthright_Gallery_CoverImage_72.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(2387,2,'2015-02-12 17:11:46','2015-02-12 22:11:46','Limited Edition of 3: 48\" x 72\" (LA &amp; NYC auctions only)\r\nLimited Edition of 10: 20\" x 28\"\r\nOpen Edition: 11.5\" x 16\"\r\n\r\n<strong>Medium:</strong> Photograph on Hot Press Archival Paper, 330 GSM','Awaiting Delivery in the North Rift Valley, Kenya','','publish','open','open','','awaiting-delivery-in-the-north-rift-valley-kenya','','','2015-02-13 17:05:22','2015-02-13 22:05:22','',0,'http://theroadgallery.